386→                        <div id="content">Is it true that if $A\subset \mathbb{R}^2$ is a set of $n$ points such that every subset of $3$ points determines $3$ distinct distances (i.e. $A$ has no isosceles triangles) then $A$ must determine at least $f(n)n$ distinct distances, for some $f(n)\to \infty$?</div>
387→                        <div id="problem_id"><a href="/657">#657</a>: <a href="#cite-Er73-657" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er73','657'); return false;">[Er73]</a><a href="#cite-Er75f-657" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er75f','657'); return false;">[Er75f,p.101]</a><a href="#cite-ErPa90-657" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('ErPa90','657'); return false;">[ErPa90]</a><a href="#cite-Er97e-657" onclick="event.preventDefault();addNewBox('Er97e','657'); return false;">[Er97e]</a></div>
